      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, large piles of unsold stock in the backroom are a strong warning sign of poor business health, as they tie up crucial cash that could be used for marketing, new designs, or paying employees. Even if your initial inventory turnover number seems fine, sudden spikes in stagnant goods often indicate market misalignment or outdated trends that could eventually force drastic markdowns and erode profits. You should prioritize identifying these slow-moving items immediately so you can either discount them to free up space or remediate sizing/merchandise to improve movement before they become a total loss. Addressing this proactively is far cheaper than dealing with the financial hit of inventory write-offs that often accompany bloated stock levels.",
